<dl id="s17033ac"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="us17" href="#s17033ac">Ithaca: </a><a href="../../FF/unbs/s17all.htm#s17033ac">sector 33(ac)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Leiodes wooers&apos; seer begs but is killed</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Now <mark>Leiodes took hold of the knees of Odysseus eagerly, and besought him</mark> and spake winged words: &lsquo;I entreat thee by thy knees, Odysseus, and do thou show mercy on me and have pity. For never yet, I say, have I wronged a maiden in thy halls by froward word or deed, nay I bade the other wooers refrain, whoso of them wrought thus. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> <mark>Then Odysseus</mark> of many counsels looked askance at him, <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> <mark>caught up a sword</mark> in his strong hand, that lay where Agelaus had let it fall to the ground when he was slain, <mark>and drave it clean through his neck</mark>, and as he yet spake his head fell even to the dust. <small> Butcher &amp; Lang, trans. <a name="OHBL3" href="/udra/udex.htm#OHBL3"><cite title="source">The Odyssey Of Homer</cite></a> (1906), 369</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
